OGD_EF_GRANT_DTL_RPT.PROJECT_DESC: The Shaw Tribal Ranch Project will consist of designing a pasture layout for the ranch based on rangeland condition, topography, and existing infrastructure.  The layout will be the basis for incorporating the pasture rotation system.  Activities will include installing uplands cross fencing, installing waterway / riparian zones- specific fencing, and developing watering points in accordance with the pasture design.  The ranch has five windmills and two capped artesian well water sources.  Therefore, no well development will occur, but waterline and stocktank infrastructure will be constructed.  The existing ranch roads will be inspected.  Roads that can be eliminated, will be.  Roads that need erosion and runoff controls will have those constructed.  The waterways / riparian zones will have, if needed, Induced Meandering passive structures installed.  Induced meandering is based on fluvial geomorphological principals and strived to stabilize channels by inducing increased sinuosity and increasing native riparian vegetation.
OGD_EF_GRANT_DTL_RPT.SUBJECT: NPS - The Navajo Nation

OGD_EF_GRANT_DTL_RPT.PROJECT_DESC: This project will assist New Hampshire Department of Environmental Services (NHDES) in implementing the approved Section 319 Nonpoint Source (NPS) Management Program.  This grant provides Fiscal Year 2012 Section 319 Incremental funds for staff support and projects designed to restore waters impaired by nonpoint source pollution.  Nonpoint source pollution is caused by rainfall or snowmelt moving over and through the ground. As the runoff moves, it picks up and carries away natural and human-made pollutants, finally depositing them into lakes, rivers, wetlands, coastal waters and ground waters. Projects emphasize watershed-based planning and project implementation to solve high priority nonpoint source water quality problems.

OGD_EF_GRANT_DTL_RPT.GEOCODING_RESULTS: FLUNK GEOCODE - COULD NOT VERIFY STREET
OGD_EF_GRANT_DTL_RPT.PROJECT_DESC: This assistance agreement provides full federal funding in the amount of $150,000.  The Shaw Tribal Ranch Project will consist of designing a pasture layout for the ranch based on rangeland condition, topography, and existing infrastructure.  The layout will be the basis for incorporating the pasture rotation system.  Activities will include installing uplands cross fencing, installing waterway / riparian zones- specific fencing, and developing watering points in accordance with the pasture design.  The ranch has five windmills and two capped artesian well water sources.  Therefore, no well development will occur, but waterline and stocktank infrastructure will be constructed.  The existing ranch roads will be inspected.  Roads that can be eliminated, will be.  Roads that need erosion and runoff controls will have those constructed.  The waterways / riparian zones will have, if needed, Induced Meandering passive structures installed.  Induced meandering is based on fluvial geomorphological principals and strived to stabilize channels by inducing increased sinuosity and increasing native riparian vegetation.  SEE CONDITION NUMBERED 16.
OGD_EF_GRANT_DTL_RPT.SUBJECT: NPS - The Navajo Nation

OGD_EF_GRANT_DTL_RPT.PROJECT_DESC: This assistance agreement provides full federal funding in the amount of $150,000.  The Shaw Tribal Ranch Project will consist of designing a pasture layout for the ranch based on rangeland condition, topography, and existing infrastructure.  The layout will be the basis for incorporating the pasture rotation system.  Activities will include installing uplands cross fencing, installing waterway / riparian zones- specific fencing, and developing watering points in accordance with the pasture design.  The ranch has five windmills and two capped artesian well water sources.  Therefore, no well development will occur, but waterline and stocktank infrastructure will be constructed.  The existing ranch roads will be inspected.  Roads that can be eliminated, will be.  Roads that need erosion and runoff controls will have those constructed.  The waterways / riparian zones will have, if needed, Induced Meandering passive structures installed.  Induced meandering is based on fluvial geomorphological principals and strived to stabilize channels by inducing increased sinuosity and increasing native riparian vegetation.  SEE CONDITION NUMBERED 16.

OGD_EF_GRANT_DTL_RPT.PROJECT_TITLE: CEP - IDEM - SECTION 319 WATERSHED MANAGEMENT - FY 2004
OGD_EF_GRANT_DTL_RPT.GEOCODING_RESULTS: GOOD - ALL EDITS PASSED
OGD_EF_GRANT_DTL_RPT.PROJECT_DESC: Under the provisions of the Clean Water Act (CWA) Section 319(h), this Assistance Agreement will fund the Indiana Department of Environmental Management (IDEM) Watershed Management Section and 24 nonpoint source projects to implement watershed restoration action strategies (WRAS), restoration of waters that have been listed as imparied under Section 303(d) of the CWA, develop and implement watershed-base plans that identify the causes and sources that will need to be controlled to achieve needed load reductions to meet water quality standards and to include an information/education component to enhance public participation in designing and implementing the needed management measures.  EPA has been working with the States to realign programs to strengthen support for watershed-based environmental protection, wherby local stakeholders join forces to develop and implement watershed-based plans that make good sense for the particulat conditions found within the communities.  The watershed approach is a coordinating framework for management that focuses public and private sector efforts to address the highest priority water-related problems within geographic areas, considering both surface and ground water flow. The watershed approach is commonly characterized by four principles: a)diverse, well integrated partnerships; b) a specific geographic focus; c) action driven by environmental objectives and by strong science and data; and d) coordinated priority setting and integrated solutions.

OGD_EF_GRANT_DTL_RPT.PROJECT_DESC: The Wisconsin Nonpoint Source Pollution Abatement Program provides financial assistance for the following four activities: 1) Local Implementation Assistance - The Wisconsin Nonpoint Source Pollution Abatement Program provides financial assistance for watershed project implementation in two ways: Local Assistance Grants and DNR's Nonpoint Source Grants; 2) Cooperative Agreement with US Geological Survey for NPS evaluation monitoring - The purpose of this project is to determine if the types and levels of best management practices identified in the Priority Watershed Plans achieve the desired decrease in the pollutant concentrations and loadings in rural and urban streams; 3) Nutrient Management Implementation Project - The State of Wisconsin proposes to help farmers implement nutrient management plans on every Wisconsin farm in a cost-effective, environmentally sound, producer-led manner; 4) Lake Partnership Projects Big Muskego, Silver and Vern Wolf Lakes - To eliminate the existing rough fish community though application of rotenone, treat the lake alum to inactive the availability of phosphorous from the lake sediments and restock the lake with game fish.

OGD_EF_GRANT_DTL_RPT.PROJECT_DESC: To provide assistance to San Carlos Apache Tribe to implement on-the-ground projects to control nonpoint sources of pollution.  Workplan Tasks: (1)  Training of staff. (2)  Continue Water Quality and Habitat Monitoring. (3)  Continue Development of Baseline WQ/Habitat database. (4)  Implement exclusion fencing and upland solar-powered livestock watering well plan. (5)  Continue implementation of the rest-rotation/deferred grazing management plan. (6)  Continue implementation of the fisheries and wildlife enhancement plan. (7)  Continue implemenation of post-project monitoring plan of north side of Bonita Creek. (8)  Prepare/Submit Quarterly progress Reports. (9)  Prepare/Submit Final Progress Report.  The specific details are in the approved workplan.
